# {{ cluster_name }}

Cloud usage for the `{{ cluster_name }}` cluster over the last 12 months.
Data comes from the [`cloud` GitHub release](https://github.com/2i2c-org/data/releases/tag/cloud).

```{code-cell} python
:tags: [remove-input]
import pandas as pd
import plotly.express as px

# Read in the data for this cluster (these were generated by generate_pages.py)
CLUSTER = "{{ cluster_name }}"
df_hub = pd.read_csv("{{ cluster_name }}-by-hub.csv", parse_dates=["date"])
df_unique = pd.read_csv("{{ cluster_name }}-unique.csv", parse_dates=["date"])
df_month = pd.read_csv("{{ cluster_name }}-month-end.csv", parse_dates=["date"])

# These are for the little number boxes at the top
current_mau = int(df_unique["unique_users"].iloc[-1]) if not df_unique.empty else 0
peak_mau = int(df_unique["unique_users"].max()) if not df_unique.empty else 0
```

## At a glance

| Current MAU | Peak MAU (12mo) |
|---:|---:|
| {eval}`current_mau` | {eval}`peak_mau` |

## Active users by hub

```{code-cell} python
:tags: [remove-input]

order = (
    df_hub.groupby("hub")["users"].mean()
    .sort_values(ascending=False).index.tolist()
)
fig = px.area(
    df_hub.sort_values("date"),
    x="date", y="users", color="hub",
    category_orders={"hub": order},
    title=f"Active users by hub on {CLUSTER}",
    labels={"users": "users"},
)
fig.show()
```

